"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923995","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-22","<p>The National Diet and Nutrition Survey (NDNS) provides information on intakes of vitamins and minerals and blood indicators of status.</p><p> </p><p>Latest NDNS data (2014/15-2015/16) show that mean vitamin D intakes were a fifth to a third of the recommended amount in all age groups, and low blood vitamin D levels were seen in 26% of older children (11-18 years) and 17% of adults (19-64 years).</p><p> </p><p>Low blood folate levels, indicating risk of anaemia, were found in 28% of older girls, 15% of older boys and 7% of adults.</p><p> </p><p>54% of older girls and 27% of adult women had low iron intakes, and iron deficiency based on blood samples was found in 9% of older girls and 5% of adult women.</p><p> </p><p>There was also evidence of low intakes of vitamin A, riboflavin, zinc, magnesium, potassium and selenium in some age groups.</p><p> </p><p>Results of the NDNS are available to view at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-diet-and-nutrition-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/national-diet-and-nutrition-survey</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-06-22T10:20:43.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923995/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923995/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-14","Deficiency Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the proportion of people who are deficient in essential vitamins and minerals.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","153897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923996","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-20","<p>As with the vast majority of NHS services, the commissioning of palliative and end of life care is a local matter, over which individual clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have responsibility. CCGs are best placed to understand the needs of local populations and fund services to meet those needs from the overall resource allocations they receive.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-06-20T11:10:55.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923996/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923996/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-14","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what funding is available for palliative care services.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","153898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923997","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-20","<p>The Improving Access to Psychological Therapies (IAPT) programme began in 2008 and has transformed treatment of adult anxiety disorders and depression in England. Over 900,000 people now access IAPT services each year, and the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health has pledged to expand services further to see 1.5 million people treated for mental health problems every year by 2020/21 alongside improving quality. Although IAPT does not provide complex interventions for dementia, IAPT practitioners are able to treat common mental health disorders such as depression and anxiety which people with dementia may present with.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-06-20T11:12:00.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923997/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923997/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-14","Dementia: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what talking therapies are available for dementia patients.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","153899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923998","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-06-20","<p>No substantive assessment of the savings to the public purse of unpaid carers has been made. Estimates of the value of unpaid care are frequently based on the cost of providing formal social care services as a direct substitute for unpaid care, and range widely.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-06-20T11:13:05.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923998/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/923998/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-06-14","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the saving to the public purse of unpaid carers.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","153900"
