"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924089","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-06-19","<p>We have raised our concerns about Mr Tofla Ndele's case at the highest levels of government in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and will continue to do so. I raised the case with the DRC Foreign Minister on 12 April. Consular officials in Kinshasa have visited Mr Ndele regularly since his detention in September 2017, most recently on 19 April 2018. Following our initial lobbying, Mr Ndele was able, in March 2018, to have a visit from a family member for the first time since his arrest.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-06-19T15:16:19.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924089/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924089/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-06-14","Democratic Republic of Congo: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on securing the return of Mr Tofla Ndele from the Democratic Republic of Congo to his family in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","153715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924090","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Secretary of State for Transport has regular discussions with the Leader of the House on a wide range of issues. The NPS was laid on 5 June and will be subject to a debate and vote in the House of Commons within 21 sitting days of laying the final NPS in Parliament. The last date that can take place is 9 July 2018.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-19T12:17:49.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924090/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924090/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Airports: National Policy Statements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has discussed with the Leader of the House the date on which the final vote on the Airports National Policy Statement is planned to take place.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924091","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Government has no plans to make any further assessments of the removal of the Lakeside Energy from Waste plant. The proposed Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) at para 5.142 makes clear that the effects of removing the plant will require assessment by an applicant for Development Consent. The proposed Airports NPS also sets out the requirements on an applicant for the management of the waste generated by the development.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","153794","2018-06-19T14:09:22.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924091/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924091/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Lakeside Energy from Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the page 92 of the Government’s response to the Transport Committee’s report, Airports National Policy Statement, published on 23 March 2018, HC 548,  what plans he has to make an assessment of the removal of the Lakeside energy from waste plant upon capacity for treatment of waste to be carried out by Heathrow Airports Ltd under the Airports National Policy Statement.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924092","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Government is clear that the Northwest Runway scheme at Heathrow will be financed by the private sector without Government support. In the event that Heathrow Airport Limited were unable to finance its scheme, there would be no default cost to Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Government and its advisers have undertaken considerable assurance work on the financial viability of Heathrow Airport Limited's scheme. Given the transformative nature of the scheme, there will almost certainly be various risks and challenges that will need to be addressed as the scheme design and regulatory framework are developed. The Government has concluded that, so far as can be assessed at this early stage of the process, in current market conditions Heathrow Airport Limited appears in principle to be able to finance expansion privately and without Government support.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-19T15:49:18.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924092/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924092/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Heathrow Airport Limited","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the cost to the public purse in the event that the Airports National Policy Statement is approved by Parliament but Heathrow Airport Limited is unable to finance its expansion.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924093","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Government is clear that the construction of the Northwest Runway at Heathrow will be financed entirely by the private sector. Should the Airports National Policy Statement not be approved by Parliament, there would be no financial liability on the Government.</p><p> </p><p>There is no agreement in place between HAL and the Department that gives rise to a right to claim for damages, losses, liabilities, costs and/or expenses or any other relief.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-19T14:01:59.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924093/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924093/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Heathrow Airport Limited","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the cost to the public purse in relation to Heathrow Airport Limited in the event that the Airports National Policy Statement is not approved by Parliament.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924094","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-19","<p>The Government has no plans to make any further assessments of the removal of the Lakeside Energy from Waste plant. The proposed Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) at para 5.142 makes clear that the effects of removing the plant will require assessment by an applicant for Development Consent. The proposed Airports NPS also sets out the requirements on an applicant for the management of the waste generated by the development.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","153791","2018-06-19T14:09:22.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924094/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924094/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Airports: Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 92 of Government’s response to the Transport Committee’s report, Airports National Policy Statement, published on 23 March 2018, HC 548, whether that accounts for hazardous waste separately to other categories of waste.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924095","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-21","<p>The Government has not undertaken a separate assessment of how long it would take to relocate the plant because relocation is not necessary from a statutory or policy perspective. However if relocation was to take place, the Airports Commission estimated that the process may take five years.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-06-21T16:30:11.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924095/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924095/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Lakeside Energy from Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of how long the relocation of Lakeside Energy from Waste will take in the event of a third runway being constructed at Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924096","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-06-19","<p>As part of its work to make the UK the safest place in the world to be online, the Government published the Internet Safety Strategy Green Paper in October 2017 and published its consultation response in May this year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The consultation response included a draft statutory social media code of practice. This provides guidance to social media providers on appropriate reporting mechanisms and moderation processes to tackle abusive content. By setting out clear standards for industry, we will make sure there is improved support for users online, and that more companies are taking consistent action to tackle abuse.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government will continue to consult with tech companies, charities and other stakeholders on the draft statutory social media code of practice ahead of the publication of a joint DCMS and Home Office White Paper.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-06-19T13:23:30.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924096/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924096/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-06-14","Social Media: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to his Department's green paper on internet safety strategy, published in October 2017, when his Department plans to publish the codes of practice for social media companies.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","153904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924097","Department for Transport","false","2018-06-21","<p>In the Appraisal of Sustainability (AoS) that accompanies the proposed Airports National Policy Statement (NPS), the Government has undertaken a high level assessment of the effect on the water environment of the Heathrow Northwest Runway scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The proposed Airports NPS sets out the requirements in relation to water quality and resources which any applicant for a Development Consent Order would need to meet. This potentially includes the effects on water bodies or protected areas under the Water Framework Directive.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not estimated the time it will take to decontaminate land. This a matter that would need to be addressed as part of any application for development consent. The AoS identifies a range of sources and pathways for contamination within the site boundary. These include two active landfills, 16 historic landfills and 11 registered pollution incidents, five of which are classified as significant.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","153797 ; 153798","2018-06-21T16:24:39.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924097/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/924097/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-06-14","Heathrow Airport: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the water bodies required to prevent a deterioration of water body status in the event of a third runway being constructed at Heathrow.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","153796"
